<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06046057 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06046057 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  CALIFORNIA; CONGRESS; EMPLOYEE; PROGRAM; EMPLOYMENT; END  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  Twenty percent of the state Senate's staff, 196 employees, have left under anincentive program designed to help meet budget-cut requirements of Proposition140, the Senate said Thursday.;    The Rules Committee said 175 staffersresigned under a program that offered them up to five months of severance payif they left by Jan. 31.;    Another 21 employees have retired to qualify fortwo years of extra retirement credit. The deadline for employees to take thatoffer is Feb. 28.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  California News  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  196 STATE SENATE STAFFERS TAKE SEVERANCEOFFER AND LEAVE JOBS  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  California News.  </MEMO><TEXT>     Bob Forsyth, a spokesman for Senate President Pro Tem David Roberti, D-LosAngeles, said the departures resulted in a savings of about $1 million in thecurrent fiscal year.;    Cliff Berg, the Rules Committee's executive officer,said staff layoffs would probably be needed in addition to the voluntarydepartures to meet Proposition 140 requirements.;    The ballot measure,approved by the voters in November, requires the Legislature to cut its budgetby nearly 40 percent starting in the coming fiscal year. It also imposes termlimits on lawmakers and other state elected officials and bars legislatorsfrom qualifying for additional legislative retirement benefits.;    A total of441 Assembly staffers have taken advantage of the severance pay-retirementbonus package, about 29 percent of the lower house's staff. Michael Reese, aspokesman for Assembly Speaker Willie Brown, D-San Francisco, said it hadn'tbeen determined how much the departures had saved.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Associated Press  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  Sacramento  </CITY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  SAN JOSE MERCURY NEWS  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910215  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Fri